WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:01.519
in GAN variations.

00:02.304 --> 00:07.915
They introduced the reasoning behind this so that there's an intuition right here.

00:09.413 --> 00:16.019
And you can see already, in practice, equation one may not provide sufficient gradient for G to learn well.

00:16.700 --> 00:22.185
Early in learning when G is poor, D can reject samples with high confidence because they're clearly different from the training data.

00:22.205 --> 00:38.880
In this case, this saturates rather than training G to minimize that, we can train G to maximize log D. This objective function results in the same fixed point for the dynamic, but provides much stronger gradients in early, much stronger gradients early in learning.

00:38.860 --> 00:47.637
This is in contrast to like other papers that simply say, oh, we do this and they at least say it provides the same fixed point, right?

00:47.938 --> 00:53.950
Yeah, so again, they're trying to convince you that this is doing something useful and that this is easier.

00:53.930 --> 00:55.152
Okay.

00:55.172 --> 01:09.009
So this strategy is analogous to other things training, maintain samples, um, from a Markov chain from one learning step in the next order to avoid burning in a Markov chain in another loop of learning.

01:09.029 --> 01:09.389
Sorry.

01:09.410 --> 01:09.610
Okay.

01:09.630 --> 01:10.851
This is from another paper.

01:10.891 --> 01:13.795
So their point here is that it's analogous.

01:13.775 --> 01:33.218
to other papers that use these Markov chains where you always do one step in G and one step in D. We alternate between K steps of optimizing D and one step of optimizing G because you have this inner maximization over D and then the outer maximization, outer minimization over G.

01:33.198 --> 01:39.149
So this has already been around the fact that you kind of have to have these optimizations in lockstep.

01:39.169 --> 01:45.361
But the difference here is you don't need any sort of like Markov chain in the inner loop and so on.

01:45.381 --> 01:46.984
You simply need back propagation.

01:48.046 --> 01:50.751
So here's an illustration of how that might

01:50.731 --> 01:51.252
work.

01:51.512 --> 01:58.422
So at the beginning here, you have your Z space, and this is always sampled uniformly, as you can see right here.

01:58.682 --> 02:00.345
This is from a prior distribution.

02:01.006 --> 02:15.386
And through the mapping, so this here is from Z to X is G. So this is the mapping G. You can see that the uniform distribution is now mapped to something non uniform, which results in the green thing.

02:15.406 --> 02:17.329
So G is the green line.

02:17.309 --> 02:22.417
while as this is data, the black dots are data.

02:23.399 --> 02:31.972
And if you have a discriminator, the discriminator is supposed to tell you where there's data and where there's fake data.

02:32.593 --> 02:34.997
Now, so green here is fake.

02:37.053 --> 02:40.378
Now this blue line is sort of a half trained discriminator.

02:40.518 --> 02:42.221
Now you train D, right?

02:42.361 --> 02:49.052
You maximize D the discriminator, and that gives you this blue line right here.

02:49.212 --> 02:54.080
So this is a perfect discriminator for these two data distributions.

02:55.101 --> 03:00.630
It tells you it's basically the ratio of green to black at each point.

03:00.610 --> 03:04.981
And now you train the generator according to this.

03:05.141 --> 03:13.542
And you can see that the gradient of the discriminator is in this direction.

03:14.244 --> 03:16.830
So it's like up this hill.

03:16.810 --> 03:24.466
And that's why you want to shift your green curve over here according to the gradient of the discriminator.

03:24.827 --> 03:35.950
Note that we first trained the discriminator and now in a second step we optimize the generator.

03:35.930 --> 03:44.081
So now we shift this green curve over in order to along the gradient of the blue curve.

03:44.842 --> 03:49.027
So it's important the green curve doesn't see the black curve ever.

03:49.628 --> 03:51.310
The generator doesn't see the data.

03:51.350 --> 03:58.680
The generator simply sees that blue curve and it goes along the gradient of that blue curve of the discriminator.

03:58.660 --> 03:59.121
Okay.

03:59.702 --> 04:13.085
And then if you do this many, many steps, actually there are dots right here, you will end up with a discriminator that has no clue what's where this is one half probability everywhere because the ratio is the same.

04:13.626 --> 04:23.082
And you will end up with the probability of data equal to the probability of the output generated samples.

04:23.888 --> 04:28.873
And this can happen if the generator simply remembers the training data.

04:29.113 --> 04:31.255
But there are a number of things that counter that.

04:31.476 --> 04:38.463
For example, the generator is continuous while the training data is, of course, discrete.

04:38.843 --> 04:44.769
So there is this in-between things right here where there is no training data.

04:45.210 --> 04:49.494
In fact, to hit exactly training data is very, very unlikely.

04:49.514 --> 04:53.558
But of course, you can still peek at the training data.

04:53.538 --> 05:04.368
But also, I think there are two things why the generator doesn't simply remember the training data first because it doesn't ever see the training data directly.

05:04.749 --> 05:08.560
So it can only see it through the discriminator.

05:08.540 --> 05:22.656
And second of all, because it is built as these multi-layer neural networks, it doesn't have the power to just remember this because as there is kind of this notion of continuous function.

05:23.156 --> 05:27.361
So, and the, these neural networks are rather smooth functions often.

05:27.902 --> 05:34.429
And therefore I think that is something that helps the generator avoid remembering the training data.

05:34.713 --> 05:38.697
Of course, there is still this problem of mode collapse that was really big in GANs.

05:38.757 --> 05:45.845
So even if it doesn't remember the training data, it might focus on the easiest part of the training data and forget all other parts.

05:46.205 --> 05:51.111
And that was a direct result, actually, of this objective.

05:51.591 --> 05:52.812
So where was it?

05:53.453 --> 06:04.585
So this objective directly led to mode collapse in some form because it penalizes different errors differently.

06:04.565 --> 06:10.035
Of course, people have come up with ways to solve that.

